This project has pushed forward the principled use of data in science and applications in two central directions. The first direction concerns the formulation and rigorous analysis of learning tasks arising in machine learning and inverse problems, adressing some of the new challenges that the increasing complexity of models and the growing size of data sets have brought to the foundations of both optimization and Bayesian approaches. The second direction concerns the development and analysis of optimization and sampling algorithms to be employed in data-driven applications involving complex, high dimensional systems. This project has brought these two research directions together by establishing a strong connection between statistical consistency and algorithmic scalability: well-posed problems are often computationally tractable, and a key principle for the design of scalable algorithms is to exploit statistical consistency wherever present.

This project has led to eight research publications with five overarching themes:

i) the analysis of continuum limits of discrete objects defined on random data;

ii) the study of new regularization techniques;

iii) the design and analysis of scalable sampling algorithms;

iv) the use of surrogates for complex models;

v) the sound quantification of uncertainty.

Contributing to this wide range of themes required close collaboration between the authors. More broadly, the PIs have fostered research collaboration between and within their institutions, and have also established new interdisciplinary collaborations. In addition, a central part of the PIs' work has been devoted to mentoring graduate students that have benefited from the breadth of mathematical ideas and applications of this project. The PIs have disseminated the research outcomes in numerous seminars and conferences.



